719
00:30:49,108 --> 00:30:50,761
I FEEL LIKE A FLAPPER.

720
00:30:50,805 --> 00:30:52,676
YOU SHOULD HAVE SEEN ME
DO THE CHARLESTON.

721
00:30:52,720 --> 00:30:54,069
YOU ARE LOVELY.

722
00:30:59,814 --> 00:31:01,555
OPERA... OPERA...

723
00:31:02,382 --> 00:31:03,600
JAZZ...

724
00:31:03,644 --> 00:31:05,864
BORING, BORING, SNORING.

725
00:31:06,516 --> 00:31:07,735
I AM DRUNK.

726
00:31:08,910 --> 00:31:11,043
I HATE BEING DRUNK.

727
00:31:11,086 --> 00:31:11,870
FUNNY,
I DON'T MIND IT.

728
00:31:12,522 --> 00:31:13,567
EVER.

729
00:31:16,700 --> 00:31:17,484
MY GOODNESS.

730
00:31:18,920 --> 00:31:20,008
YOU THINK YOU KNOW A MAN--

731
00:31:20,661 --> 00:31:21,618
BARRY MANILOW.

732
00:31:24,621 --> 00:31:27,102
PLAY ME
SOMETHING SWINGING.

733
00:31:27,146 --> 00:31:31,019
I WANT TO DANCE
AND FORGET ALL THIS...
THIS STUFF.

734
00:31:31,063 --> 00:31:32,107
OH, YEAH,
BECAUSE YOU KNOW...

735
00:31:34,240 --> 00:31:36,372
SOMEBODY'S GOING TO DIE ALONE
TODAY, AREN'T THEY?

736
00:31:39,549 --> 00:31:41,421
WHAT WAS ON YOUR
POST-IT, MASON?

737
00:31:47,688 --> 00:31:50,386
NOW, CAN I SHOW YOU
THE OUTSIDE STORAGE?

738
00:31:50,430 --> 00:31:52,127
I'D LOVE TO SEE THAT.
HONEY?

739
00:31:52,171 --> 00:31:53,259
IN A SECOND, I JUST
WANT TO GET A FEEL

740
00:31:53,302 --> 00:31:54,738
FOR THE HOUSE
ONE MORE TIME.

741
00:31:54,782 --> 00:31:56,175
OKAY.

742
00:31:56,218 --> 00:31:57,959
[T.V. PLAYING]

743
00:32:14,584 --> 00:32:15,542
[SHUTS T.V. OFF]

744
00:32:17,674 --> 00:32:18,937
SO, REGGIE,
WHAT WERE YOU WATCHING?

745
00:32:20,112 --> 00:32:21,504
NOTHING.

746
00:32:24,290 --> 00:32:26,379
WHAT'D YOU MEAN
WHEN YOU SAID
YOUR SISTER COMES BACK?

747
00:32:28,033 --> 00:32:29,338
SHE VISITS US.

748
00:32:29,382 --> 00:32:30,557
AND YOU TALK TO HER?

749
00:32:31,601 --> 00:32:33,952
NOT LIKE FACE TO FACE.

750
00:32:33,995 --> 00:32:36,519
SO SHE CHECKS UP ON YOU,
SEES IF YOU'RE OKAY?

751
00:32:38,130 --> 00:32:39,174
I GUESS.

752
00:32:44,136 --> 00:32:45,224
ARE YOU?

753
00:32:52,883 --> 00:32:54,189
I DON'T THINK
YOU SHOULD MOVE HERE.

754
00:33:00,587 --> 00:33:02,545
WHERE WAS HER FAVORITE SPOT
IN THE HOUSE?

755
00:33:04,939 --> 00:33:06,593
HER ROOM, I THINK.

756
00:33:07,637 --> 00:33:09,422
SHE DIDN'T REALLY
TELL ME THINGS.

757
00:33:12,642 --> 00:33:14,253
I THINK WE SHOULD GO BACK
TO THE WAFFLE HAUS.

758
00:33:14,296 --> 00:33:15,471
IF YOU MISS A REAP,

759
00:33:15,515 --> 00:33:17,343
A WRATH WILL BE
VISITED UPON YOU

760
00:33:17,386 --> 00:33:18,866
AS SUCH WILL HAVE
YOU WRITHING

761
00:33:18,909 --> 00:33:20,520
IN TESTICLE-SHRIVELING HORROR.

762
00:33:20,563 --> 00:33:21,608
THAT WAS RUBE.

763
00:33:21,651 --> 00:33:22,957
WHY DO YOU
DRINK SO MUCH?

764
00:33:23,001 --> 00:33:24,567
YOU'RE SO LOVELY.
I LOVE YOU.

765
00:33:24,611 --> 00:33:26,787
YOU'RE SO PERFECT,
AND YOUR SKIN
IS JUST SO BEAUTIFUL.

766
00:33:26,830 --> 00:33:28,441
TRUE, BUT NOT WHAT I ASKED.

767
00:33:31,009 --> 00:33:34,969
IT'S PEOPLE'S IMPERFECTIONS
THAT MAKE THEM SO BEAUTIFUL.

768
00:33:35,013 --> 00:33:37,537
LIKE BLACK VELVET
THAT SHOWS OFF
A LITTLE DIAMOND.

769
00:33:38,233 --> 00:33:40,583
THOSE THREE FRECKLES

770
00:33:40,627 --> 00:33:42,455
THAT SHOW OFF
YOUR ALABASTER SKIN.

771
00:33:42,498 --> 00:33:43,804
CUT THE BULLSHIT, MASON.

772
00:33:43,847 --> 00:33:47,112
WHAT, DAISY?

773
00:33:47,155 --> 00:33:49,940
REALLY, WHAT,
IN THE WHOLE GODDAMN
SCHEME OF THINGS,

774
00:33:49,984 --> 00:33:51,420
IS ONE MORE UNHAPPY SOUL?

775
00:33:53,466 --> 00:33:54,815
I JUST CANNOT CARE ANYMORE.

776
00:33:58,123 --> 00:33:59,863
I CANNOT CARE ANYMORE.

777
00:34:07,132 --> 00:34:08,916
YOU SAW THE POST-IT
BEFORE YOU LOST IT.

778
00:34:08,959 --> 00:34:10,178
NO.

779
00:34:12,833 --> 00:34:14,356
YES, YOU DID.

780
00:34:14,400 --> 00:34:16,402
YOU ALWAYS LOOK AT IT
WHEN YOU GET IT,

781
00:34:16,445 --> 00:34:17,751
EVEN FOR JUST A SECOND.

782
00:34:17,794 --> 00:34:19,187
NO, I DON'T.

783
00:34:19,231 --> 00:34:20,362
DO I?

784
00:34:21,015 --> 00:34:22,190
I WATCH YOU.

785
00:34:23,974 --> 00:34:26,325
YOU NEVER JUST PUT IT
IN YOUR POCKET.

786
00:34:26,368 --> 00:34:27,978
DO YOU WATCH ME?

787
00:34:28,022 --> 00:34:30,459
YOU ALWAYS LOOK AT IT,
BECAUSE YOU'RE CURIOUS.

788
00:34:30,503 --> 00:34:31,678
YOU WANT TO KNOW.

789
00:34:33,288 --> 00:34:34,550
WHAT DO I WANT
TO KNOW?

790
00:34:35,595 --> 00:34:36,944
THEIR NAME.

791
00:34:38,989 --> 00:34:41,514
WHERE THEY'RE
GOING TO DIE.
YOU'RE CURIOUS.

792
00:34:41,557 --> 00:34:42,776
YOU ALWAYS
LOOK AT IT.

793
00:34:42,819 --> 00:34:43,777
YEAH.

794
00:34:46,171 --> 00:34:47,607
SOMETIMES,
I DO LOOK AT IT.

795
00:34:49,609 --> 00:34:51,393
AND YOU LOOKED
AT THIS ONE, TOO.

796
00:34:52,873 --> 00:34:54,527
AND THIS PERSON
WON'T DIE ALONE.

797
00:35:06,843 --> 00:35:09,107
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

798
00:35:09,150 --> 00:35:10,412
<i>THIS IS A GHOST STORY,</i>

799
00:35:11,674 --> 00:35:13,633
AND IT'S A LOVE STORY.

800
00:35:15,330 --> 00:35:18,377
IT'S ABOUT A MAN
WHO LOVED A WOMAN.

801
00:35:20,074 --> 00:35:23,251
<i>A MAN WHO THOUGHT
THE FLAME OF THEIR LOVE</i>

802
00:35:23,295 --> 00:35:24,731
<i>COULD NEVER DIMINISH.</i>

803
00:35:29,170 --> 00:35:30,389
<i>BUT IT DID.</i>

804
00:35:31,694 --> 00:35:35,524
WHAT HAD ONCE BEEN A DANCE
HAD BECOME...

805
00:35:36,873 --> 00:35:38,136
A BATTLE.

806
00:35:39,441 --> 00:35:40,877
THEY FOUGHT AND FOUGHT.

807
00:35:43,576 --> 00:35:45,055
IN THE DEAD OF NIGHT,

808
00:35:46,927 --> 00:35:51,410
AFTER ANGRY WORDS
WERE SPOKEN...

809
00:35:53,716 --> 00:35:57,981
<i>HE LEFT THEIR BED
AND SADDLED HIS HORSE.</i>

810
00:36:01,028 --> 00:36:03,422
<i>AND SHE SAID TO HIM,</i>

811
00:36:03,465 --> 00:36:05,641
"IF YOU DON'T COME BACK
IN THREE DAYS,

812
00:36:06,903 --> 00:36:09,079
"THEN YOU CAN
NEVER COME BACK.

813
00:36:09,123 --> 00:36:10,646
"MARK MY WORDS...

814
00:36:13,083 --> 00:36:14,302
I'LL BE GONE."

815
00:36:14,346 --> 00:36:16,391
WELL, WHERE WOULD SHE GO?

816
00:36:16,435 --> 00:36:19,089
TO LIVE WITH
AN OLD BOYFRIEND
FROM HIGH SCHOOL?

817
00:36:19,133 --> 00:36:20,700
I THINK YOU TWO ARE
A LITTLE AHEAD OF THE STORY.

818
00:36:22,745 --> 00:36:23,833
AM I GOING TO BE
INTERRUPTED AGAIN?

819
00:36:26,880 --> 00:36:29,709
ANY OTHER QUESTIONS,
THOUGHTS?

820
00:36:30,318 --> 00:36:31,493
QUERIES?

821
00:36:32,755 --> 00:36:34,409
THEN I WILL CONTINUE.

822
00:36:36,585 --> 00:36:37,934
STILL ANGRY...

823
00:36:40,067 --> 00:36:41,764
STILL ANGRY,
THE MAN RODE AWAY...

824
00:36:43,940 --> 00:36:46,334
<i>AND HE ENJOYED THE SOLITUDE.</i>

825
00:36:46,378 --> 00:36:48,206
<i>THE NOISE OF THEIR ARGUMENT</i>

826
00:36:48,249 --> 00:36:52,122
<i>WAS REPLACED
BY THE SOOTHING SOUNDS
OF THE FOREST.</i>

827
00:36:52,166 --> 00:36:53,428
[TWIGS SNAPPING]

828
00:37:03,699 --> 00:37:05,701
<i>BUT AFTER JUST TWO DAYS
IN THE FOREST,</i>

829
00:37:06,354 --> 00:37:07,790
<i>HE GREW LONELY.</i>

830
00:37:09,662 --> 00:37:11,316
<i>HE WAS FILLED WITH REGRET.</i>

831
00:37:14,667 --> 00:37:17,974
<i>HE WANTED TO RETURN
TO THE WOMAN HE LOVED,</i>

832
00:37:18,018 --> 00:37:20,238
<i>AND HE WANTED TO RETURN
TO THE LIFE THAT HE MISSED.</i>

833
00:37:21,804 --> 00:37:23,676
HE FOUND A SHORTCUT
THROUGH THE WOODS,

834
00:37:23,719 --> 00:37:25,286
<i>AND HE TOOK IT.</i>

835
00:37:25,330 --> 00:37:26,896
<i>HE WAS DESPERATE,</i>

836
00:37:26,940 --> 00:37:28,507
<i>DESPERATE TO GET BACK
TO THE WOMAN HE LOVED</i>

837
00:37:28,550 --> 00:37:29,638
<i>BEFORE IT WAS TOO LATE.</i>

838
00:37:30,683 --> 00:37:32,598
HER THREATS RANG IN HIS HEAD.

839
00:37:32,641 --> 00:37:33,990
WOULD SHE WAIT FOR HIM?

840
00:37:34,034 --> 00:37:35,383
OR WOULD SHE BE TRUE
TO HER WORDS?

841
00:37:35,427 --> 00:37:36,471
WOULD SHE BE GONE?

842
00:37:40,519 --> 00:37:42,564
HE COULD FEEL HIS HORSE
LOSING SPEED,

843
00:37:45,132 --> 00:37:46,786
AS IF IT WOULDN'T MAKE IT
THROUGH THE NIGHT.

844
00:38:08,286 --> 00:38:09,461
[DOG BARKING]

845
00:38:15,162 --> 00:38:16,337
[GUNSHOT]

846
00:38:16,381 --> 00:38:17,773
WHAT WAS THAT?

847
00:38:17,817 --> 00:38:19,688
DOUBLE-BARREL 12-GAUGE,
FULL CHOKE.

848
00:38:19,732 --> 00:38:22,038
DO WE NEED TO GO
AND HELP SOMEBODY?

849
00:38:22,082 --> 00:38:22,996
THAT WAS SWEET, FRANK.

850
00:38:27,696 --> 00:38:29,176
I'M JUST A STORYTELLER.

851
00:38:29,219 --> 00:38:30,917
GREGG HERE'S
IN CHARGE. GREGG?

852
00:38:30,960 --> 00:38:33,049
OH, HO... NO.

853
00:38:33,093 --> 00:38:35,748
NO, I-I-I DON'T THINK SO.

854
00:38:35,791 --> 00:38:37,358
I'M A LITTLE AFRAID
OF THE TREES AT NIGHT.

855
00:38:39,969 --> 00:38:42,537
WELL, WE CAN EITHER
STOP NOW OR GO ON
WITH THE STORY.

856
00:38:42,581 --> 00:38:43,712
IT'S UP TO YOU GUYS.

857
00:38:43,756 --> 00:38:45,018
NO MORE
INTERRUPTIONS. HMM?

858
00:38:46,193 --> 00:38:47,368
OKAY?

859
00:38:47,412 --> 00:38:48,761
HOW YOU DOING, CRYSTAL?

860
00:38:48,804 --> 00:38:50,197
YOU'RE ABOUT TO LOSE
YOUR MARSHMALLOW.

861
00:38:53,113 --> 00:38:55,768
<i>THE MAN CAME TO THE EDGE
OF A DARK AND UNKNOWN SWAMP.</i>

862
00:38:57,813 --> 00:39:00,250
<i>HE HAD TO MAKE A DECISION.</i>

863
00:39:00,294 --> 00:39:01,861
SHOULD HE GO
INTO THE SWAMP

864
00:39:01,904 --> 00:39:03,166
OR GO AROUND IT?

865
00:39:05,734 --> 00:39:09,042
DOES HE GO THROUGH THE SWAMP
OR DOES HE GO AROUND IT?

866
00:39:09,085 --> 00:39:10,739
WE ALL ASK OURSELVES
THAT QUESTION, DON'T WE?

867
00:39:14,003 --> 00:39:16,354
<i>IT'S A VERY SCARY QUESTION
TO ANSWER ALL ALONE.</i>

868
00:39:21,271 --> 00:39:23,143
EXCUSE ME. EXCUSE ME.

869
00:39:23,186 --> 00:39:24,449
YOU'VE GOT
SOMETHING I NEED.

870
00:39:24,492 --> 00:39:25,624
I'M SORRY?THE POST-IT.

871
00:39:25,667 --> 00:39:27,408
IT'S MINE.
I NEED IT.

872
00:39:27,452 --> 00:39:28,670
THEN MAYBE
YOU CAN TELL ME

873
00:39:28,714 --> 00:39:30,803
WHY IT HAS
MY NAME ON IT.

874
00:39:30,846 --> 00:39:32,413
I CAN'T DO THAT.
I'M SORRY.

875
00:39:32,457 --> 00:39:33,893
I'M SORRY.

876
00:39:37,549 --> 00:39:39,072
[RUBE]:  <i>AND NEXT TO
THE SWAMP WAS A BOY.</i>

877
00:39:42,423 --> 00:39:43,424
MY NAME IS...

878
00:39:43,468 --> 00:39:45,339
HEY!

879
00:39:45,383 --> 00:39:46,862
[RUBE]:  <i>THE MAN ASKS THE BOY,</i>

880
00:39:46,906 --> 00:39:50,170
<i>"TELL ME, DOES THE SWAMP
HAVE A HARD BOTTOM?"</i>

881
00:39:50,213 --> 00:39:51,040
[GUNSHOT]

882
00:39:52,433 --> 00:39:54,392
AND THE BOY TELLS
THE MAN IT DOES.

883
00:39:56,219 --> 00:39:59,745
<i>SO THE MAN GUIDES HIS HORSE
INTO THE SWAMP.</i>

884
00:40:02,487 --> 00:40:04,010
[DOG WHIMPERING]

885
00:40:10,582 --> 00:40:13,889
<i>AND AS HE BEGINS TO SINK</i>

886
00:40:13,933 --> 00:40:16,979
<i>DEEPER AND DEEPER
INTO THE SWAMP,</i>

887
00:40:17,023 --> 00:40:19,112
<i>HE SAYS TO THE BOY,</i>

888
00:40:19,155 --> 00:40:21,114
<i>"I THOUGHT YOU SAID
IT HAD A HARD BOTTOM."</i>

889
00:40:26,467 --> 00:40:29,339
<i>AND THE BOY SAYS, "IT DOES."</i>

890
00:40:31,516 --> 00:40:32,908
"YOU'RE JUST NOT THERE YET."

891
00:40:37,435 --> 00:40:39,393
SO THE MAN DOESN'T GET BACK
TO HIS WIFE IN TIME?

892
00:40:40,089 --> 00:40:41,264
HE MIGHT.

893
00:40:41,308 --> 00:40:42,962
HE MIGHT GET OUT
AND REACH HER, RIGHT?

894
00:40:44,180 --> 00:40:45,443
THAT'S THE END
OF THE STORY, FOLKS.

895
00:40:47,096 --> 00:40:48,663
I MEAN, HE MIGHT
GET BACK TO HER.

896
00:40:49,272 --> 00:40:50,796
GUYS...

897
00:40:53,015 --> 00:40:54,495
HI. WHAT DID I MISS?

898
00:40:54,539 --> 00:40:56,366
A WONDERFUL STORY.

899
00:40:56,410 --> 00:40:58,064
MILLIE, I'VE BEEN WORRIED
ABOUT YOU.

900
00:40:58,107 --> 00:40:59,500
WE HEARD A GUNSHOT, AND--

901
00:40:59,544 --> 00:41:00,719
OH, I'M FINE.

902
00:41:01,371 --> 00:41:02,590
OKAY.

903
00:41:02,634 --> 00:41:04,418
JUST DON'T GO OFF ALONE
LIKE THAT AGAIN.

904
00:41:05,158 --> 00:41:05,941
RUBE?

905
00:41:07,247 --> 00:41:08,814
THANK YOU.THANK YOU.

906
00:41:15,777 --> 00:41:19,477
SO, WAS THE STORY
YOU TOLD SCARY?

907
00:41:19,520 --> 00:41:21,130
OH, I DON'T KNOW.
I DIDN'T HEAR IT,
I JUST TOLD IT.

908
00:41:22,654 --> 00:41:24,438
SMART MOUTH.

909
00:41:24,482 --> 00:41:25,874
I THINK IT WAS
A LITTLE SCARY.

910
00:41:28,877 --> 00:41:31,576
YOU KNOW WHY PEOPLE
LIKE TO GET TOGETHER

911
00:41:31,619 --> 00:41:33,316
TO HEAR THESE KINDS
OF STORIES IN THE WOODS?

912
00:41:34,187 --> 00:41:35,275
WHY DON'T YOU TELL ME?

913
00:41:37,930 --> 00:41:39,148
THEY LIKE
TO FACE THEIR FEARS...

914
00:41:40,280 --> 00:41:41,324
TOGETHER.

915
00:41:44,240 --> 00:41:46,112
IT'S SOMEHOW EASIER
THAN FACING THEM ALONE.

916
00:41:51,378 --> 00:41:53,989
WOULD YOU LIKE
A "SOME"?A WHAT?

917
00:41:54,033 --> 00:41:55,556
IT'S WHAT I'VE CHRISTENED

918
00:41:55,600 --> 00:41:56,862
THE COMBINATION
OF GRAHAM CRACKER
AND CHOCOLATE,

919
00:41:56,905 --> 00:41:58,516
LIGHTLY TOASTED
OVER AN OPEN FLAME.

920
00:41:59,734 --> 00:42:00,996
WE'RE OUT OF MARSHMALLOWS.

921
00:42:01,519 --> 00:42:02,345
"SOME"?

922
00:42:03,738 --> 00:42:04,870
AH, IT'S BETTER THAN NOTHING.

923
00:42:07,046 --> 00:42:08,308
I'LL SEE YOU TOMORROW.

924
00:42:11,441 --> 00:42:12,181
YOU'RE NOT STAYING?

925
00:42:13,400 --> 00:42:16,229
OH, I'VE GOT AN EARLY
BREAKFAST MEETING.

926
00:42:16,272 --> 00:42:17,491
YOU ENJOY THE REST
OF THE RETREAT.

927
00:42:22,322 --> 00:42:24,759
[GEORGE]:  <i>MAYBE IT WAS JUST
THE WARMTH OF THE FIRE,</i>

928
00:42:24,803 --> 00:42:27,806
<i>BUT FOR ONCE, I WAS HAPPY
TO HAVE A SPOT IN THE CIRCLE.</i>

929
00:42:37,293 --> 00:42:39,078
<i>DELORES AND I
DROVE BACK TOGETHER,</i>

930
00:42:39,121 --> 00:42:41,254
<i>AND SHE TOLD ME
THAT SHE, TOO, WAS A CAT.</i>

